		 	<span id="comment_score_64297266" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64297266); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>5</a>, Interesting)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a href="//slashdot.org/~Dan+East">Dan East</a>  <span class="uid"><a href="//slashdot.org/~Dan+East">( 318230 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64297266">		
		on Thursday March 07, 2024 @10:43AM (<span class="ind"></span><a href="//developers.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23249968&amp;cid=64297266">#64297266</a>)
		<small><a href="//slashdot.org/~Dan+East/journal/" title="Sunday December 05, 2010 @07:26PM" class="user_journal_display">Journal</a> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64297266"><p>This is just a superficial fix to underlying problems in LLMs. If you have to engineer your question such a very specific manner that the AI produces a correct answer, then you're merely adding another layer of crap on top to try and patch your system to work correctly.</p><p>Imagine a company produces a math processor chip that always gets the operation 4 + 4 wrong and produces 7. So to fix that the UI on top converts 4 + 4 into 4 + 4 + 1 before feeding it to the processor. That's pretty much what prompt engineering is doing but in a vastly more complex, nebulous and often biased way.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64297266">
<span class="ind"></span><a id="reply_link_64297266" class="btn link" href="//developers.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23249968&amp;op=Reply&amp;threshold=1&amp;commentsort=0&amp;mode=thread&amp;pid=64297266" onclick="D2.replyTo(64297266); return false;">Reply to This</a> 	<a href="#" class="comment_share_toggle btn link">Share</a>
